alright team, here's the gist of what's going on regarding the status of the service:

yesterday we deployed a new validation stack that performs a more trust-worthy hardware attestation.
Due to this update, the new attestation performance is worse, thus we split the validation into two parts; full & lightweight
 - full attestation takes a longer time (20-30mins), and occurs when the system first sees the miners' executors or after 12hrs
 - lightweight happens every 15mins, asserting the availability of the miners' executors

Unfortunately this strategy got exploited almost immediately, by having miners switching on/off their executors.

This flicking of the GPUs is causing an executor that was previously validated, to be re-validated (offline executors need to be full-validated again when they turn back online). 

As a result, this creates a strain in the network, as currently we perform the full validations in a serial flow. Thus, it creates a backpressure in the work queue, whereby new legit miners that just connected, need to wait even to 2-3 hrs.

The reason why you see on/off executors, is because of this delay, the TTL expiration of executor's availability is due sooner thatn we can re-eval.

Thus if the miners' executors don't get re-evaluated on time are considered offline (due to the lack of healthy heartbeat from the light re-evaluation).

And, as a result this is causing the degrade of service.

next step actions :
- We're working to see how we can reduce the time of hardware attestation, so the backpressure that I described can ease
- the lightweight checks can run on parallel and not be affected by this backpressure. So the validated miners will be ok.
- for the new miners, I'm thinking of a priority queue or maybe a penalty-timeout for the miners that "exploit" this, by having their GPUs on/off.

will try to support any other case as it comes. but that's the root cause of evil since yesterday.
